Food lies European inflation
The main reason for the inflation rise in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 Eurozone countries, the rate was higher in November than expected – after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
The official forecast is only 3 percent, Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British, and Canadian banking, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced its main interest rate; according to your opinion, the falling interest rate would favor the rise in raw materials prices and the slight decline in unemployment the formation of an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below 2 percent, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the gap: inflation needs to be “absorbed” to exclude the need for further action.
In November, the inflation rate reached a record twelve-year height; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increased food and energy prices are responsible for increasing inflation in the euro area.
MATIF wheat notes have risen by 88 percent, and the rate for soya beans has also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also had a significant decline in 2007.
The world market price of raw oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per phase of black gold reached almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to lower interest rates twice.
