There are many places where disinfectants are saved.
More than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to an incorrect treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overload of the beds, the overload of the staff - all the factors that are not precisely adequate to the prevention of infections, says the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, desinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János Hospital recently a MRSA infection was diagnosed.
The antibiotic resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly later the man had to return with a MRSA infection. An important operation has not been performed since that time due to the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
By December 10, this year, 1094 infections triggered by multiresistant pathogens from hospitals were to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections triggered by multiresistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one-third of people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) mostly react well to antibiotics, they are well healable.
However, if the drugs are overdosed or incorrectly applied, the well-responsive bacteria are antibiotic resistant, which rapidly spread in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poor functioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the hospital’s daily life.
You should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, said Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA is only not there where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, the care staff wears rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment,” says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are delivered to the hospital, although the patients are examined for MRSA, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Examples are rarely
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the inhibition of the formation or spread of the multi-resistant stimulant, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection mainly occurs in hospitals and hospitals, the hospitals should examine the hospitalized patients and immediately isolate MRSA infected.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not practiced so often.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation from the state health care bank.
The majority of cases therefore come to the daylight only when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, the medical director of the Epidemiology Center said.
According to the European Union, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies are intended to be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but this directive will not always be followed by hospitals.
Among the ambulances, or patients in primary care, microbiological samples are even more rare, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Saving on the Desinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to the other by nursing staff.
This is why handwashing, or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in the hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted through tuberculosis or contact, but in local hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often even overfilled, the beds close to one another, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further points out, unfortunately, in the financially less well-placed hospitals it even happens that desinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that just favour the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be much less common there, or the further spread of the trigger can be stopped where these protective measures are followed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government Programs Against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections in control causes the health insurance huge costs, so they are fighted everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its deterioration, was recorded in the government program.
According to the first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the trend of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of multiresistant stimuli (including MRSA) as one of its priorities, as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals.
