Fodor and the 6 percent of Hungary
As the Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries consult on the Bali roadmap, in which the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol ends.
There is an intense debate between industrial and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but it would be ready to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the industrial countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
There was also an agreement on the support of developing countries.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is intended to be managed by a 16-man committee, which is expected to be at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as listed in “Piac és Profit”.
6 percent of Hungary
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports on behalf of Hungary the EU’s efforts to maintain its leadership in global climate protection measures and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured by the 1990 values), regardless of whether the "Accord after 2012" will be successfully achieved or not.
Gábor Fodor emphasized that the target of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of just 5.2 percent, while the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed to a minus of 8 percent.
The provision for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the years 1985-87 - a provision that the country will fully meet, as it is read in the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - however, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would surely enter into force only after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new, international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international, Nobel Peace Prize awarded UN Scientific Climate Change Committee in its latest report.
This would delay the emission reduction, and the rise of Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army Shows on YouTube
British army units have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
For the first time, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special units stationed in Afghanistan have since March 2006 uploaded videos of the operations against the Taliban, the BBC reports.
The captures with helmeted miniature cameras are controlled at the air force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Soldiers of the Air Force have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Defence Ministry was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Operations in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force published the videos aimed at recruiting soldiers, and as the Defense Ministry says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign operations.
Such publicated propaganda is almost free compared to traditional television advertisements, Defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message as they confirm the legitimacy of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans Advertising with Game
But the army must also fight against amateur recordings that, in addition to the carefully processed, censored recordings, it also creates into the network – such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in somewhat heuchleric, “official” propaganda films, the losses are mostly spoken, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Of course, from the war sites in Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this “gath” for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise the slightly different way, namely with the free-download shooting game "American Army", in which the player can throw into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less vivid simulation.
