Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to Political Capital’s Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the “Better Hungary Movement”, have raised the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute’s “Risk Warning Report” states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk represents the “aggravation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Zigeun and the non-Zigeun population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term.”
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is likely aimed at provoking such a dispute, the research institution said.
As, this is seen as a disappointment by the political leaders: “People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups, who now have built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian counterpart.”
It is assumed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent conflicts.
The research institution also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard would have, not least thanks to the enormous attention from the sides of domestic and foreign media, “significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the confidence in stability and democratic maturity.”
We remember that since autumn 2006 the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously rebuilding, so since summer 2007 several organizations called “national self-defense association” have been established.
“These groups are common to define themselves as a civil organization, while they openly praise to prepare their members for – sometimes armed – defence tasks (catastrophic protection, country defence, order protection), referring to the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself,” he said.
And further: all this is done according to the method that tries to shape various political efforts, based on the political and party degradation of the population, as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association, therefore, does not serve merely to overcome the legal obstacles that may arise during the process of registration in court – it is at the same time a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are an increasing risk factor for the relations with the neighbouring countries.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, so some ultranationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see in the formation of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of their own anti-Hungarian policy.
This has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he said.
From the point of view of the Research Institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an individual phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, thus the political risk for the entire region has grown.
The activities of the Hungarian Guard are similar to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced in August 2007 by the extreme-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma mass evacuations that took place in a city district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents as an occasion for the establishment of the National Guard, with the argument that the organization's goal is "national protection".
Their opinion is that in the last 17 years a fair "Zigeun terror" has been perceived in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent - said Political Capital.
And further: the initiative would have triggered a fierce debate in the Bulgarian public.
