A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now free to access.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are located at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be seen until now, unless with a “humanitarian” intention, i.e. individually and namely, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
The 11 governments, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to make them available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening is valid since yesterday.
Heavy information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable investigations to be carried out, “especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inhabitants of concentration camps and the health status of forced workers,” explains Reto Masters, the head of these archives, managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to make these named documents available to the public due to the weak nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The lists of persons in the concentration camps or the arrest orders issued by the Gestapo were compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who were deported or subjected to forced work, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to set them the way to their compensation.
Until today, more than 300 fixed employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, some of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
“There is nothing fundamental to expect in these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
