The Congress approves the MIFID Directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
Parallel to the parliamentary preparation, which today ended its session with the Congress decision in the Senate on the project-related add-on/modification proposals, the government published the provisions that arise from the new law, with the intention to enable the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of Congress and Senate Members, who in their negotiations and votes pursued the goal of setting the best possible arrangement that ensures the security of investors and regulates the individual entrepreneurial activities in order to guarantee a generally efficient market event.
In addition to the modernization of the financial markets, the MIFID, which re-establishes the Securities Services Regulation, seeks to improve the protection of investors, increase the inspection requirement of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various control authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive enables both specialized companies and natural or legal persons to provide financial advice and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESISs) to the consulting companies associated with the investment and mediation companies of securities.
Furthermore, it expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, so that the regulated circular markets will be added the multilateral systems of effect trading and the systems for the internationalization of trade orders, which will eventually compete with the current economic actors.
The law obliges investment firms to disclose the focus of their corporate profile, the confrontation and the forms of risk management on the market and to register all the projects carried out in order to facilitate CNMV their control performance.
The Economic Commission of the Congress later planned further changes, with the decision that the debt with titles must now be considered “complex” funds for the investor due to its high risk, confirmed by the U.S. mortgage and banking crisis.
In addition, the entry into force of the Directive on the legal restriction of the work areas of graduated economists was used; 30 years after the 1977 Regulation, which restricted the work areas reserved for economists, was adopted.
The Senate, on its part, determined new positions in the financial sector, as that of the economic mediator, working on a foreign account, does not require authorization from the CNMV and can offer its services to commercialize products and to gain customers simultaneously to several investment companies.
