After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo boxes, internal research at the Modern Museum in Stockholm now comes to a fevering outcome: The six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén presented to the Modern Museum in 1995, are copies - and probably also the majority of about a hundred more Brillo boxes from the "Type Stockholm" that are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is overwhelmed, a confusing network of artistic and curatory productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the popcards of the "Brillo" soap powder.
A exhibition of his works at the Modern Museum in 1968 presented - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes of paper: These did not come (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cartonagen factory.
It was not about works of art, but their patterns, merely exhibition pieces.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Modern Museum.
Time scientists are now talking about about fifteen boxes that were rightly entered into the art and auction history as authorized original Andy-Warhol-Brillo boxes with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 on auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that there were about a hundred wooden boxes produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left him.
In fact, Hulténs 105 boxes were produced only in 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol was dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Modern Museum, has, in addition to the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, also investigated three Swedish private-owned boxes, two of which were made in 1968 in Stockholm: their press panels were first grounded and scattered, then white oil color was applied with a pencil.
The structure of the 1990 copies, however, suggests that the color was applied directly to the press panel with a paint roll without grounding - in addition, it is not oil, but acrylic color.
“These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s Brillo Boxes,” says Lars Nittve, director of the Modern Museum: “If the ‘Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board’ in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Modern Museum will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition materials.”
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it will follow the “hard accusations” that are being raised regarding the soap powder boxes.
Since then, there has been an unbeatable silence.
Rebellion soldiers in Manila
In the Philippines, rebellious soldiers gave up in a hotel in Manila, calling for the collapse of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not be responsible for bloodshed, the leader Antonio Trillanes, who warned the president of corruption and election fraud, told reporters at the hotel.
Government soldiers had previously destroyed the hotel under drunk gas operation.
The two dozen soldiers had been singing in the building for hours.
About half of them stood before court on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003, including Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly stop with about 30 sympathisants.
The military policemen, who were actually to watch him, had apparently gone over to him and joined his measurement.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces blocked the district around the hotel.
The President called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have enough,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the Scout Rangers elite unit, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
